Sep 10 2009 	Surprisingly small tariff for a great experience	Sept 7-10, 2009We spent three nights here after finding an attractive rate on Expedia. Never been to this hotel previously, we are always skeptical of urban-boutique, and particularly San Francisco, hotels. I didn't want a re-do of a smallish, skid-row hotel in the Tenderloin, or what some refer to as &quot;lower Nob Hill.&quot; But even in the better sections of San Francisco, we couldn't help notice a lack of street cleaning and an increase in homelessness.Happily, this hotel is practically brand-new and well-maintained. Everything seemed to work properly. The lights work in an European fashion--a card-activated light system to reduce wasted electricity. The water pressure in the showerhead was strong. There was both a safe and mini-fridge. The bedding offered a restful sleep.As with most urban hotels, parking can be bothersome and expensive. Luckily, the Stockton-Sutter garage is across the street and offered secure and relatively cheaper parking than the alternative. There are several coffee shops and restaurants nearby. Starbuck's is diagonal to the hotel and opens at 5:30 AM. The hotel does not have morning coffee service in the lobby, but it does have complimentary newspapers.I really liked Orchard Garden Hotel especially with the pricing and location.	
