Aug 25 2009 	Great hotel excellent location	Our family of 4 - Mum, Dad and teenagers aged 16 &amp; 19 have just returned having spent 9 nights at the hotel and we were all delighted with it. Rooms were quiet, clean &amp; comfortable (beds brilliant) and bathrooms provided herbal 'eco' toiletries and large fluffy robes - a nice touch. Staff were all great - very welcoming (as was almost everyone in San Francisco), nothing too much trouble. In particular Art on the front desk was really helpful with advice on where to go and best ways to get there, and nothing was ever too much trouble. We ate breakfast a couple of mornings, and had one evening meal - food in 'Roots' was very good. Location was excellent - just a few strides from the ChinaTown Gate. We walked a lot and had no problem finding our way around. Did also use various transport - cable cars (just for the experience), buses, trams etc - transport system is excellent.On our first full day we took a 5 hour city tour with Dylan's City Tours. There were just 13 of us in a small tour bus, and Dylan is such a great guy we felt like we were travelling with a family friend - highly recommended. We also took another tour to Carmel and Monterey with Great Pacific Tours. Once again a small tour bus with just 11 passengers and a lovely tour guide, Mary. This tour includes lunch in Carmel which was in a lovely restaurant and saved us wasting our limited time looking for somewhere to eat. Also gave us an opportunity to chat with fellow travellers.Most memorable thing we did ourselves was probably Alcatraz - definitely not to be missed, but in line with comments I have seen from previous reviewers book before you travel. We pre-booked and when we visited Alcatraz there were signs up saying sold out for next 5 days. A previous reviewer refers to a 50's diner which didn't suit them - this was probably Lori's and we loved it. I'm a sucker for all the old music and enjoyed feeding the jukeboxes, but more to the point the food and the service were excellent. We much preferred it to Sear's which is highly recommended but which we found to be dark although the food was good.If you are tired in the evening and don't want to walk too far, turn left out of the hotel and walk down about a block and a half to Belden. There are several little bistros along this lane and it has a nice atmosphere. We ate in Cafe Bastille (Parisian) and B-44 (Catalan) and would recommend both. We also had a lovely lunch one day at Pier 39 - Fog Harbour Fish House - clam chowder, swordfish, crab cakes etc. - superb. We also loved the Italian district around Washington Square, North Beach where there are lots of great places to eat.If there are any mechanical/technical fans in your party, the Cable Car Museum is worth a visit. It's not just a museum, it's also the winding room providing the power for the whole system. It's very hot and noisy but very interesting.We all loved San Francisco - the climate (warm while we were there - just needed a sweater in the evening and a jacket whilst on a ferry), the people (very welcoming), the sights, the places to eat, the hotel ... really everything about the place!	
