Jun 10 2009 	I love this hotel; I'll be back.	The greenest hotel in the city, and yet it doesn't cut into the luxury! With the recent hit to the economy, prices are way more affordable, and that leaves more in the budget for eating at the excellent Roots organic restaurant downstairs.They have decent wireless Internet, as well as a wired terminal in each room. It's free, but for longer stays you have to get a new code from the front desk from time to time. This is my biggest annoyance. The Internet access was good enough to be able to watch a Netflix movie on my laptop, which is saying something.The hotel is only a block from Belden lane (a whole row of four-star restaurants!), and within sight of the tourist entrance to Chinatown. And don't forget Bart a few blocks away. Muni access is equally close, though I don't know Muni well enough to tell you how easy it would be to get to, e.g., Fisherman's Wharf. Most of my business trips to SF involve walking to an office near the Ferry Building/Embarcadero Bart, which is just about a mile from the hotel.I find the rooms to be quiet--even the ones on the street side. If you're SUPER sensitive to noise, you can request an &quot;inside&quot; room, where the view isn't as nice, but it's completely silent. The A/C system is all digital and works great. OH, except for one thing: It forgets your temperature setting when you leave your room (the keycard is required to operate the A/C), so if you go out for ice and come back, you'll need to reset your temperature, unless you like 72 degrees.Overall it's my favorite hotel in the area, and I've been to a lot of them (I go to SF once a month, on average).	
