Feb 3 2009	Pleasant	Just stayed here last wk and had a good experience. Perhaps the front desk has improved because of TA complaints but we had excellent, prompt customer service.Front desk guys were friendly and helpful. They also rushed to assist us in hailing cabs, carrying luggage etc.We were also pleased to not see hardly an homeless people and so were not badgered or made to feel unsafe during our five night stay. According to many reviews of other SF hotels this is a chronic problem. So we're not sure what to attribute it to- apparently the mayor is asking people not to give the homeless handouts so that they will avail themselves of existing services or perhaps the hotel's location was better- between Chinatown and Union Square.Someone else complained about the mattresses being uncomfortable- we thought they were quite comfy- kind of a firm foam rather than box springs but not too firm. Linens were excellent quality- seemed to be all cotton with high thread count. Climate control was good and the room could be made cool enough at night to enjoy the down duvets.Our &quot;superior&quot; room with two double beds facing the front of the hotel was quite roomy but another room facing the back with a king bed was quite small. We heard almost no noise from other guests over five nights but the king bed to the rear reported some noise issues. Street noises were also minimal in our 7th floor room.Bar service was nice and we enjoyed the free appetizers with drinks which seemed quite pricey but are probably standard for big city hotels. The dinner menu looked good but I have a fear of most hotel dining... so often mediocre.We ate breakfast one morning across the street at Cafe de la Presse- a really cute fake French place. The atmosphere was great and would definitely go there again. Breakfast was tasty although an order of toast tasted kind of old or stale.. Espresso drinks were acceptable but not great.We also ate dinner one night up the hill on Bush St at Bar Crudo. High quality ingredients and pretty good but not great unless you are a fan of sashimi.. We thought it was going to be Italian and so were disappointed in the mostly raw seafood menu. A seafood chowder was creamy and good except for cubes of lardo swimming in it. Would be improved by being plainer and less exotic.Had alot of disappointing dining experiences despite reading Zagat and SF Chronicle Best Of. RW Apple steered us wrong on the Tadich Grill- very poor food but nice atmosphere and private booths. Maybe we should have asked the hotel staff for suggestions but we didn't.Our best meals were at the Ferry Bldg. Slanted Door (Vietnamese) is excellent but very busy and expect a wait even with reservations. Also, as you face the ferry bldg, the taqueria in the bldg immediately to the left was quite tasty for lunch. Miette Bakery at the Ferry Bldg had divine pastries- bring some of their packaged cookies home as a gifts.My only minor criticism of the hotel was the daily maid service which was adequate but marginal despite leaving a good tip each day. No eye for detail- so the hotel management might want to consider hiring more females- not to be sexist.. but the maid service was marginal as I say.. kept things clean but not nicely straightened up.Would we stay here again? Yes, if a good rate was available. We had also considered the 480 which had a good expedia rate. The Orchard Garden's location is close to ideal.	
